            <section class="content-section" id="strategy">
                <h2>Strategy</h2>
                <p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Meet everyday</strong>Our remote team started meeting for 2-3 hours every day to critique any and all UI to maintain consistency </li>
                    <li><strong>Components only</strong> Many in the data space were trying and failing to deliver  tracking plan solutions. </li>
                    <li><strong>Educate</strong> Design was extremely foreign to most of the brilliant people in the company and they were hungry to understand as much as possible. </li>
                    <li><strong>Ship</strong>Every time design was pulled in was an opportunity to elevate. </li>
                </ul>
                <h3>Approach</h3>
                <ul> 
                    <li><strong>Research:</strong> I mapped the data definition and tracking plan creation and implementation workflows on our internal side as well as via interviews with customers. I also talked to coworkers about the tracking plan and implementation process at former companies they'd worked at. The result was an extremely disjointed, disparate process across tons of different tools. Everyone had similar tasks, and similar goals, they were just doing them through various hacks. </li>
                    <li><strong>Define:</strong> Conducted qualitative research through user interviews and informal testing to uncover natural voice commands and tone preferences</li>
                    <li><strong>Design:</strong> Designed, prototyped, component-tized, and polished the UI of all features. </li>
                    <li><strong>Ship:</strong> Continuously refined the look and feel of each workflow and updated based on stakeholder feedback through beta and release</li>
                </ul>
                <div class="image-placeholder">
                    <div class="thumbnail" data-caption="The timeline was tight for a giant feature like this, but the pace kept momentum high and the team focused.">
                        <img src="/img/Rudderstack/trackingplanUI.jpg" alt="timeline for tracking plans and data catalog feature">
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h3>My Role & Contribution</h3> 
                <p>I was a main product designer on a team of 3. I worked most closely with a PM and EM to define in the early stages, and then with my two design colleagues in later stages for critiques, brainstorming, and design-system implementation.</p>
            </section> 
            
            <section class="content-section" id="solution">
                <h2>Solutions</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>Users and customer success colleagues were constantly asking us for more visualization around status. </li>
                    <li>We tested a few different error states for “completed with failures” “aborted” “aborted with failures” to make them less confusing, and went with orange tags</li>
                    <li>We defined elemental relationships into the UI. Data relationships were made explicit through visual cues and interactions because the UI at Rudderstack was primarily a visibility tool.</li>
                    </ul>
                <div class="image-placeholder">
                    <div class="thumbnail" data-caption="A basic tracking plan implementation did not include a data catalog and required 4-5 different tools and 11+ steps at minimum to complete.">
                        <img src="/img/Rudderstack/syncs.jpg" alt="">          
